  <data name="FullDescription" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>A data store flagged as recording log data (StoresLogData = Yes) that also stores credentials (StoresCredentials = Yes) is a strong signal that secrets are being written into logs. Logs are typically broadly readable, aggregated, and retained for a long time, so secrets that reach them are exposed to information disclosure far beyond their intended audience.

This rule is violated for any storage element whose StoresLogData and StoresCredentials properties are both Yes.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="HelpText" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Keep secrets out of logs: redact or tokenize credentials before they are written, and store secrets in a dedicated secret store rather than the log store. Separate the two responsibilities into distinct elements and correct the StoresLogData or StoresCredentials property so only one applies to each store.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="MessageText" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Data store [{0}] records log data and also stores credentials, so secrets can leak into logs and be disclosed to anyone with log access.</value>
  </data>
